Our Node.js microservice's memory usage grows from 150MB to 1.2GB over 24 hours, then crashes with OOM. We've taken heap snapshots at 1h, 12h, and 23h. The top retained objects at 23h are:

```
Retained Size | Object
  412 MB      | (array) in EventEmitter._events.data
  298 MB      | (array) in Map (connectionHandlers)
  89 MB       | (string) in Set (processedIds)
```

Here's the relevant code:

```javascript
class MessageProcessor extends EventEmitter {
  constructor() {
    super();
    this.connectionHandlers = new Map();
    this.processedIds = new Set();
  }

  registerConnection(connectionId, socket) {
    const handler = (data) => {
      this.processedIds.add(data.messageId);
      this.emit('data', { connectionId, payload: data });
      // ... process message
    };
    this.connectionHandlers.set(connectionId, handler);
    socket.on('message', handler);
  }

  handleDisconnect(connectionId) {
    this.connectionHandlers.delete(connectionId);
    console.log(`Connection ${connectionId} cleaned up`);
  }
}

// In the server setup:
const processor = new MessageProcessor();

wsServer.on('connection', (socket) => {
  const connId = generateId();
  processor.registerConnection(connId, socket);

  socket.on('close', () => {
    processor.handleDisconnect(connId);
  });

  processor.on('data', (event) => {
    metrics.record(event);
  });
});
```

We handle about 500 connections/hour, with average session duration of 10 minutes.

We have an e-commerce system with an Order Service and an Inventory Service communicating via a message queue (RabbitMQ). Occasionally, customers can purchase items that are actually out of stock. The flow is:

1. Order Service receives purchase request
2. Order Service publishes `OrderCreated` event to queue
3. Inventory Service consumes the event and decrements stock
4. If stock goes below 0, Inventory Service publishes `StockDepleted` event
5. Order Service consumes `StockDepleted` and should cancel the order

```javascript
// Order Service
async function createOrder(req, res) {
  const order = await db.orders.create({
    userId: req.body.userId,
    productId: req.body.productId,
    quantity: req.body.quantity,
    status: 'confirmed'
  });
  await messageQueue.publish('order.created', {
    orderId: order.id,
    productId: order.productId,
    quantity: order.quantity
  });
  return res.json({ order, message: 'Order confirmed' });
}

// Inventory Service
async function handleOrderCreated(event) {
  const product = await db.products.findById(event.productId);
  product.stock -= event.quantity;
  await product.save();
  if (product.stock < 0) {
    await messageQueue.publish('stock.depleted', {
      productId: event.productId,
      orderId: event.orderId
    });
  }
}
```

We see this issue primarily during flash sales when many orders come in simultaneously for the same product. The product might have stock=5 but 20 orders get confirmed.

I'm building a type-safe data transformation pipeline in TypeScript and getting a complex type error I can't understand. The code:

```typescript
type TransformFn<TIn, TOut> = (input: TIn) => TOut;

interface PipelineStep<TIn, TOut> {
  name: string;
  transform: TransformFn<TIn, TOut>;
}

class Pipeline<TInput> {
  private steps: PipelineStep<any, any>[] = [];

  pipe<TOut>(step: PipelineStep<TInput, TOut>): Pipeline<TOut> {
    this.steps.push(step);
    return this as unknown as Pipeline<TOut>;
  }

  execute(input: TInput): any {
    return this.steps.reduce((acc, step) => step.transform(acc), input);
  }
}

// Usage:
interface RawData {
  name: string;
  age: string;
  scores: string;
}

interface ParsedData {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  scores: number[];
}

interface EnrichedData extends ParsedData {
  ageGroup: 'junior' | 'senior';
  averageScore: number;
}

const pipeline = new Pipeline<RawData>()
  .pipe({
    name: 'parse',
    transform: (raw: RawData): ParsedData => ({
      name: raw.name,
      age: parseInt(raw.age),
      scores: raw.scores.split(',').map(Number)
    })
  })
  .pipe({
    name: 'enrich',
    transform: (parsed: ParsedData): EnrichedData => ({
      ...parsed,
      ageGroup: parsed.age >= 18 ? 'senior' : 'junior',
      averageScore: parsed.scores.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0) / parsed.scores.length
    })
  });

const result = pipeline.execute({ name: 'Alice', age: '25', scores: '90,85,92' });
// result type is 'any' — I want it to be EnrichedData
// Also, the second .pipe() gives error:
// Argument of type 'PipelineStep<ParsedData, EnrichedData>' is not assignable
// to parameter of type 'PipelineStep<RawData, EnrichedData>'
```

How do I fix this so the pipeline is truly type-safe with proper inference through the chain?
